===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ja|kayu}}
{{ja-kanjitab|かゆ|yomi=k}}
{{swp|ja:}}
{{swp|Kayu}}
{{swp|Congee}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|-}}.  First attested in a portion of the ''{{w|Shoku Nihongi}}'' dated to 700.<ref name="NKDc">{{R:ja:NKD Concise}}</ref>

Further derivation {{unc|ja|nocap=1}}.  Some theories include:

* Possible shift from {{m|ja||食湯|tr=keyu|lit=food + hot water}} or {{m|ja||濃湯|tr=koyu|lit=thick, rich + hot water}}.{{rfv-etym|ja|What sources say this?}}
** However, neither of these suggested compounds are attested.
* Possible combination of {{m|ja|加|tr=ka||to add; additional}} + {{m|ja|湯|tr=yu||hot water}}.{{rfv-etym|ja|What sources say this?}}
** However, the ''ka'' reading for {{m|ja|加}} is from {{noncog|ltc|-}}, and any mixed {{noncog|ltc|-}}-{{cog|ojp|-}} compound would be extremely unlikely as early as this term is attested.
* An alternate theory suggests it is an abbreviation of {{m|ja|[[炊ぐ|炊ぎ]][[湯]]|tr=kashigiyu}}.<ref>前田富祺編著 『日本語源大辞典』 {{w|小学館}}、2005年。</ref>
** Semantically, this would seem to make the most sense, as the verb {{m|ja|炊ぐ|tr=kashigu}} refers specifically to the cooking of grains to make them edible.
*: However, a review of other sound shifts and abbreviation patterns shows that any change from ''kashigiyu'' to ''kayu'' is phonologically unlikely.
*: Another issue is that the verb {{m|ja|炊ぐ|tr=kashigu}} initially referred to the steaming of rice,<ref name="NKDc-kashigu">{{R:ja:NKD Concise|炊ぐ}}</ref> which could not have resulted in any kind of ''kayu'' or rice [[porridge]].  Only later did the practices of cooking rice shift to instead boil rice in water,<ref name="NKDc-kashigu"/> a necessary step in the making of ''kayu''.
<!--*: In addition, in terms of [[morphosyntactics]], ''kashigi'' is a verb stem, and ''yu'' is a noun.  Other nouns derived from verb stems + nouns often mean "[noun] that one [verbs]": compare {{m|ja|食べ物|tr=tabemono|t=food|lit=''mono'' or "thing" that you ''taberu'' or "eat"}}, {{m|ja|飼い犬|tr=kaiinu|t=pet dog|lit=''inu'' or "dog" that you ''kau'' or "take care of"}}.  As such, any compound ''kashigiyu'' would be expected to mean “''yu'' or "hot water" that you ''kashigu'' or "boil/steam grain to make edible"”.  This does not agree with the proposed resultative noun sense of ''kayu'', which would be more like “the ''yu'' or "hot water" that is the result after you ''kashigu'' or "boil/steam grain to make edible"”.-->

